# The for Loop

Imagine a teacher who must print 30 report cards with identical formatting. Instead of writing 30 almost-identical blocks of code, a loop repeats a block of code a fixed number of times.

Java's `for` loop is the most common loop when you know the number of iterations in advance:

```java
for (initialisation; condition; update) {
    // body — executes while condition is true
}
```

The header has three parts, separated by semicolons:
1. **Initialisation** — runs once before the loop starts: `int i = 0`
2. **Condition** — checked before every iteration; the loop stops when this is `false`: `i < 5`
3. **Update** — runs after every iteration: `i++`

```java
for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    System.out.println("Iteration: " + i);
}
// Prints: Iteration: 0, Iteration: 1, ..., Iteration: 4
```

## Counting Backwards

```java
for (int i = 5; i >= 1; i--) {
    System.out.print(i + " ");  // 5 4 3 2 1
}
```

## Custom Step Size

```java
for (int i = 0; i <= 10; i += 2) {
    System.out.print(i + " ");  // 0 2 4 6 8 10
}
```

## The Enhanced for Loop (for-each)

For iterating over arrays or collections without needing an index:

```java
int[] scores = {85, 92, 78, 95, 88};

for (int score : scores) {
    System.out.println(score);
}
```

Read this as: "for each `score` in `scores`, execute the body."

## Accumulator Pattern

Declare a variable before the loop and update it inside:

```java
int[] marks  = {72, 88, 91, 65, 84};
int   total  = 0;
int   highest = marks[0];

for (int mark : marks) {
    total += mark;
    if (mark > highest) highest = mark;
}
double average = (double) total / marks.length;
```

In the code example below, you will see a classic for loop, a for-each loop, and an accumulator applied to a student score report.

codeExample.code:
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        // --- Part 1: score analysis with for-each ---
        int[] scores  = {78, 92, 85, 67, 95, 88};
        int   total   = 0;
        int   highest = scores[0];

        for (int score : scores) {
            total += score;
            if (score > highest) highest = score;
        }

        double average = (double) total / scores.length;
        System.out.printf("Scores  : %d entries%n", scores.length);
        System.out.printf("Total   : %d%n",         total);
        System.out.printf("Average : %.1f%n",        average);
        System.out.printf("Highest : %d%n",          highest);

        // --- Part 2: times table with classic for ---
        System.out.println("\n--- 7 Times Table ---");
        for (int i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
            System.out.printf("7 x %2d = %3d%n", i, 7 * i);
        }
    }
}

